fields.title: The koilawallahs of Godda

fields.description: The koilawallahs move in lines of 8 to 20
Team effort is also important in coping with uphill stretches or while crossing a pond or stream
Men from different castes sitting down together for their meal  -  unusual in itself, even if they do not share from each other’s lunch box
When ‘parking’ a fully-laden bicycle, you use a metal rod, or a very strong wooden stick, propping up the load on one side
This overladen bike collapsed and has probably done its last journey for a while
Kishen Yadav pushing his heavy load of coal on a bicycle with reinforced bars and without a chain (since he’s removed that to reduce friction)
The loads range between 150 to 250 kilograms
Arun Sah used to push much heavier loads
Imagine trying to push this one 40-60 kilometres or more!
Puran is around 14 years old, but the strenuous labour he does makes him look older and tougher
Puran’s load is lighter, relatively speaking, but that doesn’t mean you and I can do it
With a cargo so huge, even a mild upward incline has the koilawallah struggling

The koilawallahs, or coal carriers of Godda district try earning a living by picking up coal from the waste dumps near the Rajmahal mining project at Lalmatiya and pushing huge loads of it  --  ranging from 100 to 250 kilograms  --  to Godda town 40 kilometres away
AT Moideen is one of ten farmers sharing fifteen acres in this part of the village
Lata has been with the Green Army for five years and was involved with Kudumbashree over eight years.
Padmavadi has been with the green army for four years and first heard about it through the Panchayat
Lata’s teammate takes a moment to survey the wet field before starting work on it with the transplanter.
It is on this sheet that the seeds are sown by the farmer.
Padmavadi floats sliced portions of the seedbed to the transplanter.
Lata feeds paddy mats into the arm while her partner steers the transplanter.
A small piece of paddy mat thrown to the bank.
Padmavadi, with three others combs through the fields to transplant rice in pockets missed by the transplanter arm
A.T.Moideen serves his labourers black tea and achappam.
